        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>There's a real simple reason for this: Texture memory. If they actually had a rotating, dynamic, spinning moon in game, it'd take a lot more memory to display.</P><P><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>To simulate the phases of the moon would simply require drawing a shadow across it.  Takes no texture memory at all.  Not that this is required anyway, as according to them, one side is always light and the other dark.</P><P>Now if they did want to make it rotate, all this would require is instead of using the inefficiently shaped circular texture they use now, to using a rectangular one and show different areas of it to represent different facings.  Depending on the detail level and size, this could be done without using any extra texture memory at all.</P><P>The real reason is lazyness.</P><P>So far the best explanation here is that there is a second moon we never see.  This is possible if the moon's orbit is one day, so it is always just out of sight.  If it kept the same face towards the sun at all times, it could also meet the one side day/one side night requirement too.  The light side would have daily eclipses though.</P><P>I'm not too keen on the second moon being in the plane of sky.  I've always understood planes to be alternate planes or reality, so any moon there would have nothing to do with the moons around Norrath.</P><P><IMG src="http://members.spree.com/funngames/qazjax/manapump.jpg"></P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
