        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">There is the flaw in your theory, because Norrath's moon does not actually orbit the planet, nor does it rotate on its axis.  The moon rises and sets each night as Norrath rotates on it's own axis.  Likewise, Norrath does not rotate on an orbit around the sun, or if it does, we would have to assume that it's axis is perfectly perpendicular to the sun as there are no seasons.</P><P>The moon, or Luclin, defies gravity and remains fixed in it's place in relation to Norrath.  This is why the moon always rises as the sun sets and we are always at a full moon.</P><P>The face towards Norrath is therefore always light and the opposite face is always dark, there are no tides and no seasons.</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
