        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">I think Norrath is stuck in a pocket dimension traveling at the speed of light.  The planet of Norrath itself continues at what we percieve as a 'normal' pace but the rest of the universe from our perspective is 'frozen' in time.  </P><P>If we were to travel off towards the sun, time would slow down and the relative speed of Norrath would speed up until it was a blur of motion.</P><P>Thus, to a spectator from, say, our world, the entire existence of Norrath is but a few years of our time, while thousands of years pass in Norrath between when the world is born and dies.</P><P>The moon of Luclin is on the border of the pocket dimension.  That would explain why things we take for granted behave so differently there.  The moon is frozen in time with everything else in the universe (relative to Norrath), yet travelers to it from Norrath move at the same speed as they did on Norrath.  <BR>When they look back towards Norrath, things appear normal, but if they continued outward from the moon...  no telling what would happen.</P><P>It is amazing that being right on the border hasn't totally destroyed the small moon but may be all the more mysterious because of it.</P><P><BR>/ooc I quit EQ so couldn't care less about how they screw up another expansion, I just like sci-fi.  :)</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
